lli explains in detail how labor is recruited, trained, and used in the industry. He then shows how inexperienced workers are convinced to lease a truck and to work as independent contractors. He explains how deregulation and collective action by employers transformed trucking’s labor markets--once dominated by the largest and most powerful union in US history--into an important example of the costs of contemporary labor markets for workers and the general public.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aIndependent truck driverszUnited States. 0aTruckingzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  acdl truckers.  acdl.  acontemporary labor markets and long haul trucking.  aderegulation of trucking industry.  adriving a big rig.  aexploitive labor of the working class.  afreight drivers.  ahistory of trucking industry.  alabor.  along haul trucking.  aorganized trucking.  aover the road trucking.  aowner operator trucking.  asemi drivers.  atrucking industry.  atrucking labor markets.  atrucking.  aunion truck drivers.  aworking class discourse.  aworking class history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052027811040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096271240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520962712423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520962712/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY